Data analysis

Table

Text

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.63) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.04. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 17.84 (S.E. = 0.50, p < .001, 95% CI [16.86, 18.82]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.70, p = 0.912, 95% CI [-1.30, 1.46]; Std. beta = 0.02, 95% CI [-0.33, 0.37])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.42, S.E. = 0.49, p = 0.389, 95% CI [-1.39, 0.54]; Std. beta = -0.11, 95% CI [-0.35, 0.14])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 2.11, S.E. = 0.72, p = 0.003, 95% CI [0.70, 3.51]; Std. beta = 0.53, 95% CI [0.18, 0.89])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
